reviewText:
This is the well-known BBF sequel which made many players reconsider what game to buy, all thank to Dice. I bought this game for almost 5 euros, when Summer Sale 2013 was going on.
This game totally gave me another view upon FPS games, concerning graphics, physics, environment and so on. What is unique about this game is what DICE has been developing for good years>FROSTBITE. A cool thing that makes a good interrelation between Cause and Effect(s). Look for some gameplays/playthrough on YouTube, you will get it easy. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JVPu0F8kDTM

Pro:
- great environment feeling;
- teamplay;
- variety of weapons which you can customize afterwards;
- variety of vehicles, choppers, tanks- not talking about their particular model of vehicle, but their usage;
- large maps(it's not a 'cozy's camper paradise'- it just fits to all 4 classes available in the game);
- again great teamplay courtesy of each classe's duty;
- great graphics;
- astonoshing real sound.

Cons:
- can't find any at the moment;
- just to fill this space, the price should be lowered.

All in all, I would recommend it to my friends, fact that I already did it. It still diserves attention even if its successors have domninated the FPS games market. I would have played more but, I don't have that much time left for videogames because of school.

It's a must-have game! COME ON AND GET IT!

Shortly;
Battlefield Bad Company 2 was over my expectations. Even though my expectations weren't set that high, DICE really delivered yet another solid shooter. It's a great game for anyone who enjoyed the previous Battlefield games.

The long version;
In perspective to the Battlefield series;

I know many people complain about this game, and I've even heard DICE themselves say that it wasn't the best they've created. And on the last point, I need to agree, it's not the best game in the Battlefield series, not according to me. I've been along since the beginning (1942) and played all the games released in the series. The most unappealing to me was the 2142, somehow I couldn't accept the futuristic side of a Battlefield game.
That said, Battlefield 2 is to me the best game in the series (Yes, even now with 3 and 4 out.), to me, it was a more ground-breaking game than the rest of the series later have been. But, I shouldn't speak to highly of it, a big part of it now is nostalgia I've got to admit.

Singleplayer;

I played BFBC1 through the main story, and though the missions and all maybe weren't the best. I liked it, it was fun, and for BFBC2 I have to say the same. Note though that it was the characters and the story that sold me into it. If you don't appreciate the humoristic side of it, I don't think it's that much to aim for.

Multiplayer;

Here is where it excels (Remember, I only speak for my opinion.);

I didn't get the chance to play that much multiplayer on BFBC1 so I can't compare it much to that.
However, teaming up with some of your friends and jump into a squad with them, and play tactical (Okay, we didn't take it that serious, but we still teamworked.) I don't see how you can't like it. It's a great FPS, it's a really great FPS. The majority of the maps feels designed with care. The classes are fairly balanced, even though you'll be swearing alot about snipers taking you down a little bit too often. (This of course varied from patch to patch.). And the vehicle play was a treat.
With the Frostbite engine, everything looks great.
The level and weapons system is neatly created, even though it took almost to fast to unlock all the weapons considering how many levels there were left after having them all. Alternatively, you can see this as maybe there could be some more weapons thrown in the game.

On the bad side though;

The team-balance feature didn't really worked as you wanted it too. (Some of the options we're up to the servers admins, but not everything. And besides, it's not like there's always an admin online to help with the issues at hand.) If one team managed to claim a essential capture/spawn-point early in the game, it was not unusual it quickly became a so called base-♥♥♥♥ game. And then you're stuck in the rest of the game at your homebase not daring to even peak around the corner because then you'll get a snipers bullet between your eyes.
But find a good server (Or host your own!) and admins can help with this issue, at least a little bit.
I myself tried to tell my team to give them one of the spawning points if it were my team that had captured them all, to give them a fair chance, and it worked at least sometimes.

I also have to give credits to the server system, it is, according to me even better than the sequel, Battlefield 3.
I rarely had problem adding servers to my favorites or joining friends in just a click and getting into the same squad as them.

Bottom line;
If you liked the previous Battlefield games, I don't see why you wouldn't like this one. It's a different feeling sure. But according to me, that difference was a nice change to freshen up the series.
Sometimes I even preferred to boot it up instead of BF3.
It's a game I warmly recommend. And there's a numerous ways to experience it, you can play really fast and all-out-action, or you can just lurk around the small ways to find around the enemies trying to take them down one by one, it's really easy to just jump in and press play, for 20 minutes, or 5 hours.
